The holiday season is so full of joy, but also so full of comparison and feeling not enough. 
✨✨✨
I’m here to remind you that everyone’s lives aren’t as perfect as they look on the gram, our houses are all a mess, our kids misbehave in public places, we get overwhelmed and say things we have to apologize for to the ones we love most and we also wonder if we are doing enough and compare ourselves to others even though we shouldn’t! 
✨✨✨
Life is hard and messy more often then not, but it’s also an amazing gift and we each get to live our own life in our own unique ways, messes and all! So yes this is how my house looks 90% of the time, one part of the room looking all pretty and put together and another room looking like a bomb when off in it!!

This has been a year of abundant growth for me on so many levels. Both in my personal life and in my business. I feel as if though I have been broken and pieced back together multiple times this year. I’ve learned to work hard and also to rest more. I’ve learned to offer grace to others and even more to myself. I’ve learned that every day has to be a fresh start and I’m the one who has to make it that way because life is hard and we all need the opportunity to start over every single day.
✨✨✨
Growth can be both exciting and painful and we have to be open to embracing both sides and be ready for the change that comes along with growth. 
✨✨✨
I’m so thankful for all I’ve learned this year and for both what I’m taking with me going forward and what I’m leaving behind. Are you ready for big growth going into the new year?!

It is with an extremely sad heart that I share the loss of our spunky old goat 🐐 Gertie. Gertie lived a wonderful life here on our farm, she was always doing something funny, bossing the other animals around or munching on some hay. She was very close to our sweet old sheep Margo who will miss her greatly. 

It has been such a hard time on our sweet little farm lately and it feels like my heart could just break 💔. Farm life always has its ups and downs but it has been feeling like a lot more downs lately which has been so hard on my animal loving heart.

The start to our 2023 has been extremely hard. We’ve been hit with one tragedy after another on our little farm and yet I can’t help but count our blessings. I have moments were I fall into the darkness thinking why us, this is so unfair, I start to feel broken and not enough, but then I’m reminded of who’s I am and all of the love and blessings that surrounds me on all sides. 
💕💕💕
We all go through seasons of pain and difficulty and we just happen to be in one of those seasons here on our farm, but I’ve decided I’m not going to allow this season of pain to take away my joy. I have so much to be thankful for, healthy children, my own health, my sweet family and friends and all of your support. I am loved and we will continue doing our very best to care for the animals that we’ve been given to nurture and love. 
💕💕💕
If you are going through a hard season right now I’m sending you extra love and hugs and this reminder that has been popping up around me everywhere lately. 

God knows what we are going through, He is close to the broken hearted, He longs to hold us close and bring healing and hope into our lives. So today I am clinging to hope and the blessings that surround me to switch my focus from the darkness to the light. ✨
Thank you all so much for the love and support you’ve been continuing to show us, I appreciate it so very much!

Theo and Barnyard update
🐶🦆🐷🐔🐐🐑
I haven’t posted much lately about the barnyard story because we seem to be in a standstill. After our last big attack on our chickens we had no predator attacks for two weeks and a day and then the mink came back and got another one of our chickens. 
🐔
It’s now been about a month and nothing else has been attacked but we have pretty much everyone moved into the barn so it doesn’t have the opportunity to attack. We were never able to trap it even though we tried everything we knew how to do and a million other things people suggested we should try. 
🐶
So what now? Basically we are waiting until Theo is big enough to stay on patrol and out in the barnyard all night before we move the chickens, rabbits and ducks back to their regular enclosures. He is four months now and getting bigger by the day! Look how big he is already!! Around six months old Theo will be ready to stay out over night and be on patrol and at that point we will very cautiously and one enclosure at a time start moving animals back into their homes. I will continue to keep you all updated as we see how things go. (If you missed the start to the story check out our LGD highlight)

We feed her goats milk that we get from our local health food store that’s sourced from a local goat farm, they can also drink a special powdered goat formula but we have always found that their tummies do so much better on the goats milk if we are able to get it.

✨My journey to joy part 1/8✨
I’m ripping off the bandaid and showing up here with you real and raw. A few years ago I was living in a season of life where I was so broken and drowning. I didn’t even recognize the woman I had become, and my home, that was once my safe and sacred space felt like I couldn’t even be myself, because I didn’t even know who “I”was anymore. How does one get to a place like this? How do we allow ourselves to slip away little by little, somehow not even noticing that the things we held most dear to our hearts got lost somewhere along the way. 
✨✨✨
As a child all I ever wanted to be when I grew up was a mama. It’s all I could think of and dream about for years and yet somehow here I was roughly 10 years into motherhood and feeling like I could hardly make it through another day. 
✨✨✨

If you’ve been here with us for awhile you’ll remember our terrible predator problem that we had that started last fall. We had a mink that terrorized our farm for 5 months. It was absolutely horrible and we lost dozens of animals over those months. 

It was like living in a horror movie because I would lose animals over and over even after moving them and trying to protect them anyway I could. 

After months of trying to take care of things ourselves we did tons of research and decided that a guardian dog might be the best solution for our farm. 

We brought Theo home as a puppy in January, the animal deaths continued to happen while he was a young puppy, but then when he was about 6 months old he was barking and barking inside the barn one night around 11pm. I went out to see what was going on. There was tons of noise in the chicken coop, so I opened the coop and there was the link next to several dead chickens. 

Even though Theo was in the barn, he had heard the mink and the chickens and knew there was trouble and alerted us!

And Theo has been protecting our farm ever since! He’s about  to turn a year old and we are so in love with him and so thankful for how he protects our farm so well. 

He isn’t perfect, and it’s taken lots of time, patience and training to get to where we are with him today but I’m so glad that we were patient with him and that he has shown his complete loyalty to us and our sweet farm! He is a true guardian over our whole farm and I’m so thankful for him!

Are you ready to start enjoying your time as a mother again?⤵️

The other day I took the kids on a fun date by myself! We went to our local cider mill and then they chose five guys for lunch!

I remember for years I wouldn’t take all four of them out by myself because it felt too hard and overwhelming. 

We had too many bad experiences, angry outbursts and bad attitudes that I just gave up. 

But in the last year or so we have gotten back into it and it’s been so fun! 

Here’s a few things that I started doing differently to set my children up for success so that I can enjoy taking them out again;

💕I only take them out on a day that we don’t have any other big plans, my kids have a hard time with over stimulation so they can’t really control their emotions for long periods of time and now that I know this I plan accordingly 

💕I have zero expectations, not in a bad way, but in a healthy way, I’m here for the journey and the experience not for the outcome, this way I can have a calm mood no matter how their behavior is

💕I try not to rush them, if you have an agenda and a tight schedule everyone can feel that tension and it’s stressful

💕 I inform them of things we will and will not be doing or getting before we go into a store so that they know what is coming and can prepare, it doesn’t always work but it’s usually helpful and I can then remind them of our conversation if they forget

💕 I encourage them to help each other so that everything doesn’t fall on me. Bigger kids can help the younger kids, younger kids can carry things etc. they all get to help and feel part of the success of the trip

💕When someone does have big emotions I don’t make a big deal about it, I just help them work through it and take the necessary time needed to handle the situation 

✨Now I look forward to taking them all out together on a fun date! We only do it about once a month, but that keeps it pretty special so we all look forward to it!

On the final day of #nationaladoptionmonth I’m going to share some real hard honest truths because you deserve to hear them and no one told me before I adopted so I’m telling you. 

No one in the beginning phases of adoption prepares you for what life is like with an adopted child who suffers from trauma as they grow and mature and start feeling all the hard things. Adoption is beautiful, but with every adoption their is a loss of the most sacred connection and bond, the mother and the child and there is no easy way to explain how that’s natural or right or ok because it just isn’t. 

And when all the naturally hard feelings start surfacing as their mama all i want to do is help them and love them and let them know everything will be ok, but there have been times when they didn’t even want me to hug them or touch them. Every child’s hard comes through in a different way, but I’m not going to lie it has been nothing short of crippling at times for me. 

And then there’s the second hand trauma which I didn’t even know was a thing, but I’ve spent the last three years recovering from it while also working on healing myself, my children and our relationships. 

I don’t share this to be negative, I share it to be realistic, because the honest truth is adoption is really freaking hard. 

But here’s another truth, adoption is amazing and one of the best things I’ve ever done with my life. It has ripped me open and also healed me in ways I never knew I needed. It’s made me more compassionate, kind, loving, stronger, empathetic and full of grace. I would never be the woman I am today without the blessing of adoption💕

And I’ll end with this. If your heart is calling you to adoption run as fast as you can towards those sweet babies and children with open arms and an open heart, do it scared, fall madly in love and enjoy every second of it. And then find yourself an adoption community either in person or online and a therapist or counselor who specifically helps families who have adopted. You can grow a beautiful family through adoption, but you 100% are not meant to do it alone! Pray for a village and for guidance and help from others who have gone before you.💕
